    "Two main methods are considered in this context: the first involves constructing a gradientorder B-mode template and subtracting it from the observed B-mode, and the second entails employing an inverse-lensing approach.",
    "In the latter method, delensing is accomplished by remapping the lensed maps using the inverse lensing deflection angle generated by the gravitational potential.The temperature and polarization anisotropies of lensed CMB are described as:Θ(n) = Θ(n + α(n)) = Θ(n) + ∇ i Θ(n)α i (n) + O(ϕ 2), (2.1) [ Q ± i Ũ](n) = [Q ± iU](n + α(n)) = [Q ± iU](n) + ∇ i [Q ± iU](n)α i (n) + O(ϕ 2),(2.2)where tildes denote the lensed fields.",
    "We exclusively focus on gradient modes, and express the deflection angle α(n) as the gradient of the lensing potential α(n) = ∇ϕ(n) [4].In harmonic space, the E-and B-modes can be defined using the spin-2 spherical harmonics 2 Y ℓm:[E ℓm ± iB ℓm] = -dn 2 Y * ℓm (n) [Q ± iU](n),(2.3)and the harmonic coefficients of lensing potential ϕ are defined asϕ ℓm = dn Y * ℓm (n) ϕ(n).",
    "(2.4)From Eq.",
    "(2.2), the lensed E and B-modes can be written as [4] Ẽℓm= E ℓm + ℓ ′ m ′ LM ℓ ℓ ′ L m m ′ M ϕ * LM S (+) ℓℓ ′ L E * ℓ ′ m ′ + iS (-) ℓℓ ′ L B * ℓ ′ m ′,(2.5)Bℓm = B ℓm + ℓ ′ m ′ LM ℓ ℓ ′ L m m ′ M ϕ * LM S (+) ℓℓ ′ L B * ℓ ′ m ′ -iS (-) ℓℓ ′ L E * ℓ ′ m ′,(2.6)where S (±)ℓℓ ′ L is given byS (±) ℓℓ ′ L = 1 ± (-1) ℓ+ℓ ′ +L 2 (2ℓ + 1)(2ℓ ′ + 1)(2L + 1) 16π × [-(ℓ(ℓ + 1) + ℓ ′ (ℓ ′ + 1) + L(L + 1))] ℓ ℓ ′ L 2 -2 0."
